Color corrector or concealer? 
If you don’t have any discoloration then you probably won’t need to use a color corrector. But if you do then it’ll really help to neutralize the discoloration, in order for you to have a more even complexion when doing your base makeup. 

It’s a subtle change that I think makes all the difference in my base routine! 🫶🏼✨ 
___________________________________

¿Corrector de color o corrector?
Si no tienes ninguna decoloración, entonces probablemente no necesitarás usar un corrector de color. Pero si he hace falta, realmente te ayudará a neutralizar la decoloración para que la base de maquillaje luzca mejor. 

¡Es un cambio sutil que creo que marca la diferencia en mi rutina de maquillaje!🫶🏼✨

Products used ⤵️

For nail prep: 

• I always start with the Sally Hansen ‘Instant Cuticle Remover’. 
• Next I’ll use a cuticle pusher + trimmer to remove all my cuticles. 
• Then I like to buff my nails and wipe it all off with an alcohol prep pad. 
• Nail dehydrator from Modelones, to ensure that there isn’t any oil left on your nail beds. 
• YN protein bond primer to help your manicure last a bit longer. 

For the manicure: 

• Now that your nails are prepped we can go in with the gel base coat and let that cure for 60 seconds. 
• Apply your color gel of choice and let it cure. Today I used polishes from ‘modelones’ , but I also really love ‘Gaoy’ gel polish. 
• Apply your top coat and let that cure for 60 seconds. 
• And we’re done! What usually takes me the longest is nail prep and designs. My one tip for nail designs is to just do it. Once you start trying to do designs you’ll get better and more comfortable with it over time. 

.

.

.

.

.

.

Recipe below ⤵️

For the chicken marinade: 
• 2 large chicken breasts or 4-6 thighs
• 2-4 Tbsp of plain Greek yogurt 
• 1/2 lemon juice 
• 1 tbsp Kashmiri red chili (I did 2 tsp instead because a Tbsp was too spicy for me) 
• 1 tsp Tumeric 
• 1 tsp salt 
• 2 tsp cumin 
• 2 tsp garam masala 
• 1 tbsp ginger paste 
(Let it marinade at least 1-2 hrs, preferably overnight) 
For the curry: 
• neutral oil 
• 1 medium onion (I did half white and half purple) 
• 1 tbsp ginger paste 
• 3 tbsp tomato paste 
• 1 tbsp Kashmiri chili pepper (I also did 2 tsp here) 
• 1 tsp Tumeric 
• 2 tsp salt 
• 2 tsp cumin 
• 1 tsp garam masala 
• 2 1/2 cups of tomato purée 
(Let this all cook for about 5 minutes then add the chicken back in.)
• 1 1/2 cups of heavy cream (or evaporated milk if you want it lighter) 
• 1/4 cup of cilantro once it’s done cooking 

This isn’t by any means my own recipe, but I couldn’t find the creator of this recipe here on Instagram to tag her. However her tiktok handle Is @Sharmineats. This is my second time making this recipe of hers and it’s been delicious every time!! 🙌🏼

.

.

I prefer Option #1 when filming things that I can get done quick (Ex: removing items from the counter or skincare shelf, making my bed, packing things.. etc) 

I prefer Option #2 when filming things that take longer or that are convenient to have in separate clips. (Ex: cooking, grwm, skincare routine, cleaning, vlogs) 

Additional tips: 

It’s VERY important to keep your phone in the EXACT same spot if you want to make the items look like they’re moving by themselves. If your phone moves even an inch, the video won’t look seamless and the goal is to have a seamless video so that it looks like it moved around by itself. 

Also .2/.3 might be too fast if you want to create a vlog or show a specific product so I find that .5 or .6 is a better speed for those things. 

.

.

.

For the pumpkin spice syrup: 
1 cup water 
1 cup sugar 
Let these melt down to a simple syrup 
Cut the heat and add in 
1 can of condensed milk 
1 cup of pumpkin purée 
1 tsp of pumpkin pie spice 
Pinch of salt 
Blend all of these ingredients together, then strain it. 

Now you can build your latte, add in a double espresso, 3-4 tablespoons of the pumpkin spice syrup and a cup of milk. Serve hot or cold! 🤎
